05520nam a22007935i 9789400604322DE-B159720220830111616.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220830t20222022ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97894006043227 a10.1515/97894006043222doi  a(DE-B1597)635243  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 7aHIS0170002bisacsh00aIndia after World History :bLiterature, Comparison, and Approaches to Globalization /ced. by Neilesh Bose. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (264 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aGlobal Connections: Routes and Roots ;v300tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tForeword -- tChapter 1. Introduction : Globalization, Global, and World as Keywords for History and Literature -- tChapter 2. Can we have a global literary history? -- tChapter 3. World History Needs a Better Relationship with Literary History -- tChapter 4. Re-Gifting Theory to Europe : The Romantic Worlds of Nineteenth-Century India -- tChapter 5. Violence, Indenture and Capitalist Realism in Amitav Ghosh’s Sea of Poppies -- tChapter 6. Vacant Villages: Policing Riots in Colonial India -- tChapter 7. The Neoplatonic Renaissance from the Thames to the Ganges -- tChapter 8. Radical Presentism -- tChapter 9. Liberating World Literature: Alex La Guma in Exile -- tAfterword -- tAbout the Authors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  a"In the twenty-first century, terms such as globalization, global, and world function as key words at the cusp of new frontiers in both historical writing and literary criticism. Practitioners of these disciplines may appear to be long time intimate lovers when seen from pre and early modern time periods, only to divorce with the coming of Anglophone world history in the twenty-first century. In recent years, works such as Martin Puchner’s The Written World, Maya Jasanoff’s The Dawn Watch, or the three novels that encompass Amitav Ghosh’s Ibis Trilogy, have rekindled a variant of history and literature’s embrace in a global register. This book probes recent scholarship concerning reflections on global history and world literature in the wake of these developments, with a primary focus on India as a site of extensive theoretical and empirical advances in both disciplinary locations. Inclusive of reflections on the meeting points of these disciplines as well as original research in areas such as Neo-Platonism in world history, histories of violence, and literary histories exploring indentured labor and capitalist transformation, the book offers reflections on conceptual advances in the study of globalization by placing global history and world literature in conversation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 4aAsian history. 4aColonial Studies. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 4aIndia. 4aLiterary Theory, Criticism, and History. 4aLiterary studies: postcolonial literature. 4aLiterature: history and criticism. 7aHISTORY / Asia / India & South Asia.2bisacsh  aWorld history, World literature, Global history, Planetary history, Worldmaking, Globalization.1 aArac, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeecroft, Alexander, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBose, Neilesh, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBose, Neilesh, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDhar, Nandini, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElam, J. Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGommans, Jos, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKulkarni, Kedar, econtributor.4ctb4https://